<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870925-0035 </DOCNO><HL> United TechnologiesUnits Win Contracts</HL><DD> 09/25/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> UTX HON LIT MOT GM MRN COT OTRKB ROK UIS NPH TT GMHDEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF) </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Units of United Technologies Corp. got contracts totaling $95.2 million for helicopter production for the Navy and aircraft engine parts for the Air Force.    Units of Honeywell Inc. were given contracts totaling $94.4 million for tank ammunition and munitions cartridges for the Army and aircraft support equipment for the Air Force.    Litton Industries Inc. received a $62.4 million Navy contract for aircraft radar-warning receivers.    Morrison-Knudsen Corp. said a subsidiary received a five-year Navy contract totaling about $60 million to provide base support services at Fallon Naval Air Station in Nevada.    Motorola Inc. won a $56.6 million Army contract for bomb fuses and air turbine deflectors.    Colt Industries Inc. was issued a $48.2 million Army contract to produce rifles.    Chamberlain Manufacturing Corp. received Army contracts totaling $45.3 million for projectile parts.    Hughes Aircraft Co., a unit of General Motors Corp., received contracts totaling $44.6 million for TOW missile-engineering services for the Army and shipboard radar parts for the Navy.    Oshkosh Truck Corp. was awarded a $27.2 million Army contract to produce trucks.    Intercontinental Manufacturing Co. got an $18.9 million Army contract for bomb bodies.    Rockwell International Corp. received Air Force contracts totaling $18 million for Minuteman ICBM support.    Sperry Corp., a unit of Unisys Corp., was given Navy contracts totaling $17.2 million to restore combat systems of the frigate Stark and for training equipment.    TransTechnology Corp. received a $13.2 million Navy contract for chaff cartridges.    Engineered Air Systems Inc. got Army contracts totaling $12.4 million for water-purification equipment and decontamination systems.    Magnavox Government andamp; Industrial Electronics Co., a unit of North American Philips Corp., was issued a $10.2 million Navy contract for sonobuoy development. </TEXT></DOC>